> >It would appear that my 2 Votes AGAINST the 3 Vote requirement only caused
> >the supporters to cough up more support.  Fair enough.
> 
> >The reason I opposed it was that there would no longer be (and now there
> >is not) any way to cheaply pass trivial fixes and public service Proposals
> >that do not carry significant political interest.
> 
> Right.  It's time to make Disinterest meaningful again.

I'm not so sure I know what all the fuss is about. It may cost 3 VTs 
to pass a "trivial" proposal, but you get 2 VTs back as a reward for
getting it passed. How much cheaper do you want it to be? If you made
it Disinterested, so that you only had to spend 1 VT to pass it, and
you waived the rewards, then you would not end up any better off. 
When potential Zeitgeist rewards are added, you'd be better off not
making your proposal Disinterested at all.

I also don't like the old Disinterest scheme because too many
non-trivial proposal were being made Disinterested in order to make
them easier to pass. If you really want to disambiguate between 
"trivial" and "non-trivial" proposals, why not make it so that a 
player can declare eir Proposal to be Disinterested Without Objection?
If someone objects, then it must be taken that the proposal was not
as uncontraversial as the author assumed.

